<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Denies Arms Dealers' Claims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Denies Arms Dealers' Claims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0805172394 Hamburg DPA in German 1133 GMT 8 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0805172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA) -- According to the Defense Ministry, 
the Federal Government has in no case become liable to recourse 
by discontinuing deliveries to private arms dealers following 
reunification. A spokesman for the ministry thereby reacted to 
a BILD AM SONNTAG report, according to which foreign and German 
firms demand payments from the government totaling 440 million 
German marks, because the Defense Ministry failed to carry out 
arms deliveries from National People's Army stocks that it had 
promised during the time of the GDR. 
  The deliveries were agreed upon with the GDR government 
under 
former Disarmament and Defense Minister Rainer Eppelmann. The 
Defense Ministry spokesman said that with Germany's unification 
in 1990, all contracts with private arms dealers were canceled. 
Only contracts that did not violate the War Weapons Control 
Law were accepted. Following that delivery halt, the ministry 
had in fact been sued repeatedly for noncompliance with its 
contractual obligations, but it had not lost a single case. He 
added that one lawsuit was still pending, but here, too, the 
prospects of success were good. 

</TEXT>

