<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Ends Party Consultations 6 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Berlusconi Ends Party Consultations 6 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR0605111994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0926 GMT 6 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0605111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Berlusconi Winding Up Party </F>
Consultations"] 
  [Text] Rome 6 May (ANSA) -- Premier-designate Silvio 
Berlusconi will wind up his official government-formation 
consultations with political parties today, official sources 
confirmed this morning. 
  Berlusconi began the final round of consultations with a 
meeting with the (former Communist) Democratic Party of the 
Left, at 1000 local (0800 GMT). 
  At 1100 local he will meet one of his two main coalition 
partners, the hard-right National Alliance. At 1200 he will 
meet the other one, the federalist Northern League. An hour 
later he is scheduled to confer with Communist Renewal, and at 
1400 local with his own group, Forza Italia. 
  A Forza Italia official, Domenico Mennitti, after a meeting 
with Berlusconi announced that "the road to the formation of a 
new government is all downhill." 
  Berlusconi may decide to withdraw the traditional "reserve" 
on the mandate given by the president as early as Saturday [7 
May], Forza Italia Senate whip Cesare Previti commented. 
  Both officials declined to comment negotiations over the 
post 
of Interior minister. 
  Berlusconi himself said he may withdraw his reserve on 
Monday. "That would be the most logical thing to do," he told 
reporters after ending his consultations here. 
  He also forecast that the Senate debate on the new 
government 
may begin as early as next Thursday but Berlusconi stressed he 
did not want to "make commitments" on when negotiations would be 
completed. 
  "I want to be consistent with what I have already said: it 
takes time to do things well," he said, adding that he did not 
want to fix definitive dates for votes of confidence or other 
political developments. 
  Berlusconi denied he planned to withdraw his reserve 
tomorrow, saying he needed more time to fine-tune his political 
program. "I think it is correct to go to the president with a 
program, perhaps not definitive but at least with the major 
points defined, and a list of ministers," he said. 
  He declined to give any names of possible ministers and 
stressed that for the Interior Ministry, "everything still has 
to be specified." 

</TEXT>

