<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Warns Dispute With North Korea Could Go to UN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Warns Dispute With North Korea Could Go to UN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1005092594 Paris AFP in English 2307 GMT 9 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1005092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, May 10 (AFP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency warned Monday [9 May] that it could take its 
dispute with North Korea to the United Nations Security Council 
if Pyongyang peristed in serious violations of a nuclear 
inspections accord. 
  David Kyd, spokesman for the nuclear watchdog body, said 
such 
a step would be taken if, for instance, the North Koreans 
removed seals placed on nuclear fuel rods by IAEA inspection 
teams. 
  The rods are due to be changed in a five megawatt reactor in 
North Korea's Yongbyon complex, and the IAEA wants its 
inspectors there to ensure that nuclear material has not been 
diverted for military purposes. 
  Pyongyang is resisting the IAEA's conditions, and Kyd said 
its latest reply in an exchange of messages on the subject, 
received last Friday, was unsatisfactory. 
  The United States has warned that if North Korea does not 
cooperate in satisfying the international community that it is 
not developing nuclear weapons Washington would seek sanctions 
against it in the Security Council. 
  North Korea has said it would treat such a measure as an act 
of war. 

</TEXT>

