<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schaeuble Rules Out Turkey, Russia in EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Schaeuble Rules Out Turkey, Russia in EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905163394 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 9 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU0905163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["epd"-attributed report: "Schaeuble: Turkey Cannot Become </F>
EU Member"] 
  [Text] Mainz -- Wolfgang Schaeuble, chairman of the 
Christian Democratic Union [CDU]/Christian Social Union [CSU] 
Bundestag group, yesterday spoke out against Turkish European 
Union [EU] membership. "We should make it clear to Turkey that 
it cannot become a member of the European Union," Schaeuble told 
a meeting of Christian business people in Mainz. By doing so, 
one would do Turkey a favor and support the nonfundamentalist 
approach in Turkish politics. In Schaeuble's view, only such 
countries that are based on the Christian-Western tradition 
could be considered for membership to the European Union. This 
is why Russia, which apart from its European part also consists 
of an Asian part, cannot join the European Union either. At the 
same time, Schaeuble spoke out in favor of letting Turkey 
participate in the economic advantages resulting from the 
process of European unification. He also welcomed Turkish 
membership in the Council of Europe in Strasbourg. 
  Hermann Rappe, chairman of the trade union of chemical 
workers, also ruled out Turkish EU membership. In the long 
term, however, membership of Central European countries would be 
possible. 

</TEXT>

