<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   DIHT President Says Economy Prefers Kohl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DIHT President Says Economy Prefers Kohl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905163794 Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG in German 8 May 94 pp 
2-3 </F>

<F P=103> AU0905163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Hans Peter Stihl, president of the </F>
Federation of German Chambers of Industry and Commerce, by F. 
Weckbach-Mara in Bonn; date not given: "Stihl: SPD Chancellor 
Bad for the Economy"] 
  [Text] [Weckbach-Mara] Politicians are talking about an 
economic upswing. When will the Germans profit? 
  [Stihl] The recession is bottoming out, but there cannot be 
any talk about a strong upswing yet. We expect an economic 
growth of approximately 1 percent throughout Germany this year. 
At the same time, however, unemployment will continue to rise 
and will reach about 4 million this year. A slight decline is 
expected next year. 
  [Weckbach-Mara] Which government would the economy prefer 
after the elections? 
  [Stihl] The German economy will cooperate with any 
democratically elected government. However, I admit that I 
would have considerable problems with the Greens. They are 
hostile to the economy and want to lead the state back to the 
last century. 
  [Weckbach-Mara] Would you prefer a Chancellor Scharping or 
his Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD]? 
  [Stihl] With his government program, a Chancellor Scharping 
would pass on the burden of unification to the population by 
introducing a 20-percent supplementary surcharge. This is not 
fair and would be a big economic mistake. In addition, the SPD 
is planning changes concerning the taxes of family-owned 
enterprises. In many cases, a higher inheritance tax would lead 
to the sale of parts of firms or entire companies. The planned 
renunciation of nuclear energy would be unacceptable for the 
economy, and higher energy prices are against all reason. Thus, 
a changeover of power from Kohl to Scharping would have a 
negative impact on the economy and the creation of new jobs. 
  [Weckbach-Mara] Is that true? 
  [Stihl] Yes, it is. During Kohl's term of office, between 
1983 and 1993, a total of 2.7 million jobs were newly created. 
I cannot imagine that this successful development would 
continue under a Scharping government on the basis of the SPD 
program. 
  [Weckbach-Mara] It sounds as though you were completely 
happy with the current government. 
  [Stihl] No, we are not. We expect the government to 
bindingly promise the abolition of the solidarity surcharge. An 
annual examination alone is not sufficient. After three years 
at the latest, the solidarity surcharge should be gradually 
reduced. With this announcement, the government would force 
itself to save, which is necessary. It would also be useful to 
announce a fundamental reform of the social security system for 
the next legislative period. 
  [Weckbach-Mara] Do you support more retention? 
  [Stihl] Yes. One must really tell people that the existing 
social system will not be able to assume the costs for the 
treatment of diseases, for nursing care, and for old age in 20 
years' time. Thus, people should take out a supplementary 
insurance on a timely basis. A private life insurance is also 
required in addition to the pension insurance scheme, which 
numerous people already have. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

