<H3> <TI>   Government Willing To Help Turkey Join EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Willing To Help Turkey Join EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0905170894 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0905170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Addressing the 10th meeting of the European Union 
[EU] parliamentary committees in charge of European affairs, 
Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou said that if Turkey 
accepts the European principles Greece will be the first country 
to help it join the EU. Papandreou said he hopes solutions will 
be found soon to smooth Athens-Skopje relations. 
  In his address, the deputy foreign minister said the Turkish 
Cypriot community should have pursued Cyprus' accession to the 
EU. Referring to Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM], Papandreou said it must be understood that it 
is in Greece's national interest that Skopje survives. He 
added, however, that Skopje must stop violating the CSCE 
principles. 
  Chamber of Deputies President Apostolos Kaklamanis opened 
the 
conference and stressed: The continuing bloodshed in the former 
Yugoslavia is another great challenge for all of us. He 
specifically stressed the dangers facing the Balkans and greater 
Europe. Kaklamanis concluded: You realize the additional 
reasons that have caused concern for the Greek people and the 
intense interest in restoring peace. 

</TEXT>

