<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijani Ambassador: Karabakh Not Party to Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Azerbaijani Ambassador: Karabakh Not Party to Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0605180494 Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS in English 4 May 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> NC0605180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nazlan Ertan] </F>
  [Text] Ankara--Azerbaijan's acceptance to sit at the same 
table with representatives of Nagorno-Karabakh in peace talks in 
Bishkek does not mean Baku has recognized this enclave as a 
party to the Karabakh conflict, Azerbaijani Ambassador to Ankara 
said Tuesday [10 May]. 
  On the eve of the three-day peace talks hosted by 
Kyrgyzstan, 
Ambassador Mamed Novruz ogly Aliyev told the Turkish Daily News 
that Azerbaijan still regarded Nagorno-Karabakh as part of its 
territory and not as a separate party to the conflict. Novruz 
ogly's remarks flatly contradicted those of Vladimir Shumeyko, 
chairman of the upper chamber of Russian Parliament, who was 
quoted by the Interfax news agency as saying that Azerbaijan had 
stated its readiness to recognize Nagorno-Karabakh as "one of 
the parties in the conflict." Shumeyko's remarks coincide with 
new Armenian attacks north and east of Karabakh and a new round 
of peace talks in the Kyrgyz capital, Bishkek, between 
Parliament leaders from Russia, Azerbaijan, Armenia and 
Kyrgyzstan, as well as representatives from Karabakh. "We have 
sat at the same table with representatives of Karabakh in 
international meetings before. We have no objection to their 
presence. Be they of Armenian or Azerbaijani origin, they are 
representatives of our people in this enclave and we are ready 
to listen to their problems. But we do not recognize them as a 
party to the conflict," Novruz ogly said. 
  "They are there as the representatives of Karabakh. 
Nagorno-Karabakh has no Parliament and no parliamentary 
leader," he said, referring to the self-declared Karabakh 
Parliament that previously passed a resolution of annexation to 
Armenia. "They will not have the same status at the table as 
the other participants." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

