  [Text] Foreign Minister Mohamed Salah Dembri arrived in 
Athens today on a two-day visit during which he will hold talks 
with Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and with Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias, and also with the minister for 
European affairs. Over to Messaoud Boulatiour for more details 
about the visit: 
  [Begin Boulatiour recording] The main focus of the foreign 
minister's visit is the consolidation of cooperation between 
Algeria and the European Union [EU] ahead of the EU's finance 
ministers' meeting due to be held on 16 and 17 May. This 
meeting is expected to examine an EU aid package for projects to 
revive and develop the economy in Algeria, particularly as 
Greece is the current chairman of the Union. 
  Greek sources also said that Mr. Dembri's current visit to 
Greece will enable both sides to discuss the supply of Algerian 
gas to Athens. According to an agreement signed between the two 
countries, in 1996 Algeria will start exporting gas in an amount 
of between $55 and $60 million per year. By then Greece should 
have completed the construction of a pipeline in the Gulf of 
Salamis, southeast of the capital, Athens. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

