<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Not To Discuss Economics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Not To Discuss Economics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105125394 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
11 May 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU1105125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["hal"-signed report: "Yeltsin Visit: Economy on the </F>
Agenda"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 10 May -- It seems that Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin does not want to discuss problems concerning 
German-Russian economic relations during his three-day German 
visit that starts this Wednesday [11 May]. In any case, there 
is no comprehensive round of talks with representatives of 
German industry on such critical issues as Russian taxation or 
crime on the agenda. Even so, Economic Minister Guenter Rexrodt 
would like to raise the subject of taxation problems and ways of 
improving the conditions for investments, which include the 
delivery of railroad carriages for the Russian state railroad 
and the construction of a machine plant in Kamas. 
  The Economics Ministry in Bonn says that despite its 
difficult situation, Russia remains an important economic 
partner for Germany. Business with the East continues to be 
important, especially for the new laender, which exported 53 
percent of their output to Russia in 1993. Total German exports 
to Russia amounted to 11.4 billion marks [DM], and imports from 
Russia amounted to DM10.7 billion. According to the ministry, 
last year's collapse in trade between Russia and Germany has not 
continued any further. Between 1990 and 1992, trade between the 
two countries fell by almost one-half. 
  All in all, the Eastern Committee of German Industry 
considers the development of trade with East Europe and the 
post-Soviet republics as positive, despite all the difficulties. 
The increase in Russian import duties in 1994 will probably 
have a bearing on exports of microelectronic components, 
electric home entertainment equipment, and cars. It is not yet 
known to what extent general trade will be affected. All the 
same, Russia has relaxed its tough import restrictions, a move 
that affects the traditionally most important sectors of Russian 
trade -- machine and equipment construction, says the Economics 
Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

