<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Let's go to Guido Dell'Acquila at the parliament 
building in order to get the first political reactions to the 
government list. 
  [Dell'Acquila] Even before the list of ministers was 
officially released, Roberto Maroni from the Northern League 
agreed to comment on his appointment as interior minister. He 
said that it was not a victory for the Northern League, but one 
for the entire ruling coalition. He added that the Northern 
League had asked for those ministries which were essential to 
carry out its plan for reform. 
  Gianfranco Fini, leader of the National Alliance, said that 
the Berlusconi government signals the end of the First Republic 
and the beginning of an ideological swing to the right. He 
added that the government's priority objectives are the relaunch 
of the economy and social solidarity. 
  The comments of Achille Occhetto, secretary of the Party of 
the Democratic Left, were scathing. He said that the contents 
of the letter which President Scalfaro sent to Silvio Berlusconi 
revealed that the country's democracy has reached an alarming 
state and its safeguarding -- as underlined by Scalfaro -- 
should not be consigned to the vacuous reassurances of 
Berlusconi, but to permanent vigilance. 
  That's all for now. 

</TEXT>

