<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soares Promises To Mediate in Angolan Dispute </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soares Promises To Mediate in Angolan Dispute </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005213394 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
2100 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1005213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Portuguese President Mario Soares said in an 
interview that he will be pleading with Jonas Savimbi to accept 
a cease-fire compromise proposed by Angolan President Jose 
Eduardo dos Santos. Mario Soares stated that he took the 
opportunity at the Pretoria ceremony, where some 50 heads of 
state and the UN secretary general were gathered, to debate a 
number of international policy issues, particularly the urgent 
need for peace in southern Africa. He also stated that the 
urgency of a cease-fire in Angola was the main theme of talks he 
held with Butrus-Ghali and Presidents Joaquim Chissano and 
Eduardo dos Santos. In brief, President Soares' line of 
thought, shared by all those he spoke to, is that South Africa's 
example of a transition agreement based on a national unity 
government formula will have to be followed in Maputo and in 
Luanda. It was on the basis of these talks that Soares will be 
contacting Savimbi to further the Angolan peace effort. 

</TEXT>

