<H3> <TI>   International Study Group on FRY To Convene 13 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Study Group on FRY To Convene 13 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1005141294 Brussels BELGA Database in French 2031 GMT 9 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1005141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GGD: "Bosnia: Toward a Ministerial Meeting </F>
on Friday"] 
  [Text] Luxembourg, 9 May (BELGA) -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher convened a high-level meeting for Friday [13 
May] in Geneva of the study group on the former Yugoslavia, 
which includes the United States, Russia, the United Nations, 
and the European Union (EU), Luxembourg Foreign Minister Jacques 
Poos announced Monday in Luxembourg. 
  According to Willy Claes, his Belgian counterpart, it seems 
that this meeting is to be held at the ministerial level in 
order to study action to be taken in the conflict in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Mr. Poos, who made a statement at the end of a Council of 
Ministers meeting of the Western European Union (WEU), hoped 
that this meeting would revive the negotiations and contribute 
to "defining a common position among the United States, Russia, 
and the EU" to "reduce to nothing the hopes" of those who aim to 
profit from the division of the international community to make 
territorial gains, a clear reference to the Bosnian Serbs. 
  According to Mr. Claes, the EU should be represented in 
Geneva by its troika (the past, present, and future presidents 
of the Council of Ministers, namely Belgium, Greece, and 
Germany) and by the two countries which have permanent seats in 
the UN Security Council (namely France and Great Britain). 
  While emphasizing that the main parties involved in the 
Yugoslav conflict had to demonstrate their political will to 
jointly reach a cease-fire, "an essential condition for a peace 
agreement," Mr. Claes had questions about the goals and the 
final outcome of this meeting. 
  Cautiously making a number of carefully phrased remarks 
regarding the meeting, Mr. Claes did not rule out its lasting 
until Saturday, if necessary, to include a meeting of the 
countries which are providing troops for the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

