<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, Ruehe Address WEU Meeting in Luxembourg </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel, Ruehe Address WEU Meeting in Luxembourg </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905152694 Hamburg DPA in German 1229 GMT 9 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0905152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Luxembourg (DPA) -- The Western European Union 
(WEU) has decided to admit the six Central European states and 
the three Baltic countries as "associated partners." The 
foreign and defense ministers of both sides want to adopt the 
relevant documents in Luxembourg on Monday [9 May]. 
  "In this way, we have come far closer to the objective of a 
pan-European peace policy," FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
stated in his speech, which was publicized in advance. 
Meanwhile, Russia shows understanding for the extension of the 
WEU to East Europe, he said. 
  The new associated status is granted to Poland, Hungary, the 
Czech Republic, Slovakia, Bulgaria, Romania, and the three 
Baltic states. Thus, the associated partners will be able to 
attend WEU Council meetings at regular intervals in the future. 
Moreover, they get the opportunity to participate in 
humanitarian and combat missions. The East Europeans will not 
get a security guarantee. 
  FRG Defense Minister Volker Ruehe stressed in Luxembourg 
that 
Germany will do everything to create "legal and real 
prerequisites" for future WEU missions. This also includes the 
rescue of European Union citizens from places such as Yemen or 
Rwanda. 
  Kinkel announced that Bonn is basically prepared to 
participate in the development of satellite-assisted 
reconnaissance of the WEU states. However, the FRG Government 
has not yet made a final decision. Without such reconnaissance, 
which the United States ensures in NATO, the combating of crises 
by the WEU is hardly conceivable. The costs will probably be 
substantial, he said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

