<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   German, Russain Officials Hold Talks in Bonn </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    German, Russain Officials Hold Talks in Bonn </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Yeltsin Notes `Historic Reconciliation' </H4>

<F P=102> AU1105133294 Hamburg DPA in German 1142 GMT 11 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1105133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- According to President Boris Yeltsin, 
Russia wants to have peaceful relations with all its neighboring 
countries. In his toast at a dinner with Federal President 
Richard von Weizsaecker, Yeltsin said in Bonn on Wednesday [11 
May] at the beginning of his three-day visit to Germany: "For 
the first time in a long time Russia is entering the 
international stage as a major power that does not threaten 
anybody." 
  Just like Germany, Russia wants to integrate all countries 
of 
the continent into European security structures. "It is 
important that the fences and roadblocks, which have been dumped 
on the garbage heap, do not reappear." Yeltsin added: "We are 
sincerely trying to establish friendly ties with neighbors near 
and far, with all those who feel committed to the ideals of 
humanity and the standards set by international law." The head 
of the Kremlin spoke out in favor of "trade without obstacles," 
and of economic integration in Europe. 
  Yeltsin said that "a historic reconciliation" was currently 
taking place between Germany and Russia. "I am convinced that we 
can eliminate the term `war' from the Russian-German vocabulary 
for good." Yeltsin expressly praised the role of the outgoing 
federal president. "Your successor will not have things easy 
because he will be compared with Mr. Weizsaecker, who has set 
very high standards." Weizsaecker managed to remain beyond the 
emotions of everyday politics and managed to reconcile people, 
Yeltsin concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

