<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD Leader Comments on Yeltsin, Russian Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Leader Comments on Yeltsin, Russian Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205101694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0858 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Rudolf Scharping, the SPD [Social 
Democratic Party] leader and candidate for the chancellorship, 
has described the dispute, now resolved, over the farewell 
ceremony for the Russian troops as "incomprehensible and 
harmful." Following a talk with Yeltsin in Bonn today, 
Scharping said the German Government bears sole responsibility 
for the unncessary irritations which have arisen. The SPD has 
from the beginning insisted on a "worthy" farewell for the 
troops in Berlin. The talk at the Petersberg near Bonn was also 
attended by North-Rhine Westphalia Premier Johannes Rau (SPD), 
and SPD Bundestag group leader Hans- Ulrich Klose. 
  Scharping accepted an invitation from Yeltsin to visit 
Russia. An appropriate date for the visit still has to be 
discussed. 
  Scharping said that in his talk with Yeltsin he referred to 
the special importance of the "good" German-Russian relations. 
It is important for other Western states to become as strongly 
involved in Russia as the Federal Republic to lend support to 
Yeltsin's policy of political and economic reform. The SPD 
leader described economic relations between the two countries as 
"capable of being developed." He cited as examples the 
scientific, research, and technology spheres. Yeltsin stressed 
that his country wants to be a partner with equal rights in 
international organizations. 
  Yeltsin will also meet this morning with Theo Waigel, CSU 
[Christian Social Union] chairman and federal finance minister. 
Afterward, Yeltsin and Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl will set 
off on a tour of the Palatinate district. The two politciains 
are to visit Speyer Cathedral this afternoon. Yeltsin has also 
been invited to Kohl's home in Ludwigshafen-Oggersheim. 
  Yeltsin will go to Baden-Wuerttemberg tomorrow, the third 
and 
final day of his visit to Germany. 

</TEXT>

