<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Addresses National Assembly on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur Addresses National Assembly on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Other Officials Comment </H4>

<F P=102> AU1105170894 Paris AFP in English 1652 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1105170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 11 (AFP) -- French Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur demanded Wednesday [11 May] the unconditional release 
of 11 French aid workers held by Bosnian Serbs for alleged arms 
trafficking. 
  Balladur's Minister of European Affairs Alain Lemassoure 
warned the Serbs that, if they continued with their "parody of a 
trial" of the 11, Paris would regard the affair as a war crime. 
  The 11 members of the Premiere Urgence (First Emergency) 
group have been held since April 8 at the Sarajevo suburb of 
Lukavica and deny the smuggling allegations. The Bosnian Serbs 
have just extended their detention for a month pending trial and 
say the detainees could face up to 15 years in prison. 
  UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali said here Wednesday 
that he hoped to obtain the men's release. "We hope that 
through negotiation we can find a way to free the hostages," he 
said after a 45-minute meeting with Balladur. 
  Balladur assured French National Assembly deputies the 
government was "using all the means it can" to obtain its 
nationals' release. He decried that the aid workers were being 
"held hostage in the most cynical fashion". 
  The French premier also told parliament the time was 
approaching when France would have to consider if there was any 
point in continuing her presence in Bosnia if the "Great Powers" 
and the warring factions were not ready to take appropriate 
action to resolve the conflict. 
  Foreign Ministers from Europe, the United States and Russia 
are due to hold a meeting on Bosnia Friday in Geneva. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

