<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Launches Social Security Debate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur Launches Social Security Debate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1005142094 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 10 May 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BR1005142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Balladur Launches `Great Debate' on </F>
Social Security"] 
  [Text] Yesterday, Edouard Balladur announced the launch 
"this fall" of a "great national debate" on social security 
funding, following the submission of the white paper on health 
insurance reform. France is a country "in which protection, 
deemed vital by the vast majority of the population, could be 
regarded as a constraint for the economy," the prime minister 
said, but "this constraint must be fully accepted." He 
explained that social security had "a great advantage in 
preventing risks of social conflagration, which would be 
inevitable if this system did not exist." The prime minister 
warned that we "must not expect that France, like other large 
countries, can create millions of jobs which are paid scarcely 
more than one-fourth of the minimum wage...; that is not our 
social and political system." Although it is necessary to make 
"efforts" to reduce business costs, we must "think" about means 
of funding social security by "other methods." Balladur 
wondered whether it would be possible to "partly substitute, 
add, or replace" the existing funding "based on salaries" by 
"methods of funding based on consumption or revenue." This big 
fall debate will probably turn this vast and necessary reform 
into one of the themes of the presidential campaign, which 
Mitterrand's successor will have to implement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

